setTitle("Astrophysics Advanced Laboratory (2 credits)")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Introduction to techniques of modern observational astrophysics at optical and radio wavelengths through hands-on experiments. Intended primarily for juniors and seniors majoring or minoring in astrophysics. Offered in some academic years as single-term course 135 in fall, depending on astronomical conditions. (Also offered as Physics 135B. Students cannot receive credit for both courses).")
setPrereqs("course 135A and Physics 133")
setInstruct("G. Brown")
setCourse("171")
setTitle("General Relativity, Black Holes, and Cosmology")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Special relativity is reviewed. Curved space-time, including the metric and geodesics, are illustrated with simple examples. The Einstein equations are solved for cases of high symmetry. Black-hole physics and cosmology are discussed, including recent developments. (Also offered as Physics 171. Students cannot receive credit for both courses).")
setPrereqs("courses 105, 110A, 110B, and 116A-")
setInstruct("B. A. Aguirre, H. Haber")
setCourse("199")
setTitle("Tutorial")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setDiv("Graduate")
setCourse("202")
setDescrip("Radiative Processes")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Survey of radiative processes of astrophysical importance from radio waves to gamma rays. The interaction of radiation with matter: radiative transfer, emission, and absorption. Thermal and non-thermal processes, including bremsstrahlung, synchrotron radiation, and Compton scattering. Radiation in plasmas. (Formerly Electromagnetism and Plasma Physics).")
setInstruct("E. Ramirez-Ruiz")
setCourse("204")
setTitle("Astrophysical Flows")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Explores how physical conditions in astrophysical objects can be diagnosed from their spectra. Discussion topics include how energy flows determine the thermal state of radiating objects and how the physics of radiative transfer can explain the emergent spectral characteristics of stars, accretion disks, Lyman-alpha clouds, and microwave background. (Formerly 204A Physics of Astrophysics I and 204B Physics of Astrophysics II).")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("205")
setTitle("Introduction to Astronomical Research and Teaching")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Lectures and seminar-style course intended to integrate new graduate students into the department; to introduce students to the research and interests of department faculty; and to expose graduate students to teaching skills and classroom techniques. (Formerly Introduction to Astronomical Research).")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("G. Smith")
setCourse("207")
setTitle("Future Directions/Future Missions")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Examines possible key science goals for the next decade, such as planet detection, galaxy formation, and 'dark energy' cosmology; the means for addressing these goals, such as new space missions and/or ground-based facilities; and the political, technical, and scientific constraints on such research. Looks at the role of the Decadel Survey. Examines a few existing programs (DEEP, ALMA, SNAP, NGST) as examples.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("G. Illingworth")
setCourse("212")
setTitle("Dynamical Astronomy")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Surveys dynamical processes in astrophysical systems on scales ranging from the planetary to the cosmological, stability and evolution of planetary orbits, scattering processes and the few-body problem, processes in stellar clusters, spiral structure and galactic dynamics, galactic collisions, and evolution of large-scale structure.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("R. Murray-Clay")
setCourse("214")
setTitle("Special Topics in Galactic and Extragalactic Astronomy")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Survey of some principal areas of research on the origin and growth of cosmic structures and galaxies: the 'dark ages;' 21cm tomography; first galaxies; first stars and seed black holes; reionization and chemical enrichment of the intergalactic medium; the assembly of massive galaxies; quasi-stellar sources; interactions of massive black holes with their environment; extragalactic background radiation; numerical simulations and the nature of the dark matter; the dark halo of the Milky Way. (Formerly Special Topics in Cosmology)")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("P. Madau")
setCourse("220A")
setTitle("Stellar Structure and Evolution")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Survey of stellar structure and evolution. Physical properties of stellar material. Convective and radiative energy transport. Stellar models and evolutionary tracks through all phases. Brown dwarfs and giant planets. Comparison with observations.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("J. Fortney")
setCourse("220B")
setTitle("Star Formation")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Theory and observations of star formation. Observational techniques used to study star formation, particularly millimeter line and continuum observations, and infrared, visible, and UV star-formation tracers. Physics of giant molecular clouds and galaxy-scale star formation. Gravitational instability, collapse, and fragmentation. Pre-main sequence stellar evolution. Protostellar accretion disks and jets. Radiative feedback and HII regions. (Formerly Star and Planet Formation)")
setPrereqs("course 220")
setInstruct("A. The Staff")
setCourse("220C")
setTitle("Advanced Stages of Stellar Evolution and Nucleosynthesis")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("The evolution of massive stars beyond helium burning; properties of white dwarf stars; physics and observations of novae, supernovae, and other high energy stellar phenomena; nuclear systematics and reaction rates; the origin and production of all the chemical elements.")
setPrereqs("course 220A")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("222")
setTitle("Planetary Formation and Evolution")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Theory and observations of protoplanetary disks. Origin and evolution of the solar nebula. Formation and evolution of the terrestrial planets and the giant planets. (Formerly Planetary Science)")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("D. Lin")
setCourse("223")
setTitle("Planetary Physics")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Survey of interiors, atmospheres, thermal evolution, and magnetospheres of planets, with focus on the astronomical perspective. Course covers exoplanets and solar system planets, both giant and terrestrial, with attention to current and future observations.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("J. Fortney")
setCourse("224")
setTitle("Particle Astrophysics and Cosmology")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Particle physics and cosmology of the very early universe: thermodynamics and thermal history; out-of-equilibrium phenomena (e.g., WIMPs freeze-out, neutrino cosmology, Big Bang nucleosynthesis, recombination); baryogenesis; inflation; topological defects. High-energy astrophysical processes: overview of cosmic ray and gamma ray astrophysics; radiative and inelastic processes; astroparticle acceleration mechanisms; magnetic fields and cosmic ray transport; radiation-energy density of the universe; ultrahigh-energy cosmic rays; dark-matter models; and detection techniques. (Formerly Origin and Evolution of the Universe). (Also offered as Physics 224. Students cannot receive credit for both courses).")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("A. Aguirre")
setCourse("225")
setTitle("High-Energy Astrophysics")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("High-energy astrophysics and the final stages of stellar evolution: supernovae, binary stars, accretion disks, pulsars; extragalactic radio sources; active galactic nuclei; black holes. (Formerly Physics of Compact Objects)")
setInstruct("E. Ramirez-Ruiz")
setCourse("226")
setTitle("General Relativity")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Develops the formalism of Einstein's general relativity, including solar system tests, gravitational waves, cosmology, and black holes. (Also offered as Physics 226. Students cannot receive credit for both courses).")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("S. Profumo, A. Aguirre")
setCourse("230")
setTitle("Diffuse Matter in Space")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Fundamental physical theory of gaseous nebulae and the interstellar medium. Ionization, thermal balance, theory and observation of emission spectra. Interstellar absorption lines, extinction by interstellar dust. Ultraviolet, optical, infrared, and radio spectra of gaseous nebulae. (Formerly Low-Density Astrophysics)")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("231")
setTitle("Diffuse Gas In and In Between Galaxies")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Examines the observational data and theoretical concepts related to the interstellar medium (gas inside galaxies); intracluster medium (gas in between galaxies in clusters); and intergalactic medium (gas in between field galaxies). Emphases on the inferred physical conditions of this gas and its implications for cosmology and processes of galaxy formation.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("J. Prochaska")
setCourse("233")
setTitle("Physical Cosmology")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Survey of modern physical cosmology, including Newtonian cosmology, curved space-times, observational tests of cosmology, the early universe, inflation, nucleosynthesis, dark matter, and the formation of structure in the universe.")
setInstruct("B. Robertson, P. Madau")
setCourse("234")
setTitle("Statistical Techniques in Astronomy")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Introduces probability and statistics in data analysis with emphasis on astronomical applications. Topics include probability, Bayes' theorem, statistics, error analysis, correlation, hypothesis testing, parameter estimation, surveys, time-series analysis, surface distributions, and image processing. Students learn to identify the appropriate statistical technique to apply to an astronomical problem and develop a portfolio of analytic and computational techniques that they can apply to their own research.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("A. Skemer")
setCourse("235")
setTitle("Numerical Techniques")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Gives students a theoretical and practical grounding in the use of numerical methods and simulations for solving astrophysical problems. Topics include N-body, SPH and grid-based hydro methods as well as stellar evolution and radiation transport techniques.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("237")
setTitle("Accretion Processes")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Theories of spherical accretion, structure and stability of steady-state accretion disks, and the evolution of time-dependent accretion disks. Applications of these theories to the formation of the solar system as well as the structure and evolution of dwarf novae and X-ray sources are emphasized. (Formerly Accretion in Early and Late Stages of Stellar Evolution)")
setInstruct("D. Lin")
setCourse("240A")
setTitle("Galactic and Extragalactic Stellar Systems")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Structure and evolutionary histories of nearby galaxies. Stellar populations, galactic dynamics, dark matter, galactic structure and mass distributions. Peculiar galaxies and starbursting galaxies. Structure and content of the Milky Way. Evolution of density perturbations in the early universe. Hierarchical clustering model for galaxy formation and evolution.")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("240B")
setTitle("High Redshift Galaxies")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Galaxy formation and evolution from observations of intermediate-to-high redshift galaxies (z 0.5-5). Complements and builds on 240A. Cluster galaxies and field galaxies. Foundation from classic papers on distant galaxies. Recent discoveries from IR and sub-mm measurements. Impact of AGNs and QSOs. Overview of modeling approaches. Identify theoretical and observational issues. (Formerly Galactic and Extragalactic Stellar Systems)")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("G. Illingworth")
setCourse("257")
setTitle("Modern Astronomical Techniques")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Covers physical, mathematical, and practical methods of modern astronomical observations at all wavelengths at a level that prepares students to comprehend published data and to plan their own observations. Topics include: noise sources and astrophysical backgrounds; coordinate systems; filter systems; the physical basis of coherent and incoherent photon detectors; astronomical optics and aberrations; design and use of imaging and spectroscopic instruments; antenna theory; aperture synthesis and image reconstruction techniques; and further topics at the discretion of the instructor. Familiarity with UNIX, computer programming, and completion of Physics 116C is strongly recommended as well as at least one upper-division course in astronomy. Designed for graduate students; available to qualified undergraduate astrophysics majors by instructor permission.")
setInstruct("T. Jeltema, M. Bolte")
setCourse("260")
setTitle("Instrumentation for Astronomy")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("An introduction to astronomical instrumentation for infrared and visible wavelengths. Topics include instrument requirements imposed by dust, atmosphere, and telescope; optical, mechanical, and structural design principles and components; electronic and software instrument control. Imaging cameras and spectrographs are described. Offered in alternate academic years.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("C. Rockosi")
setCourse("289")
setTitle("Adaptive Optics and Its Application")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Introduction to adaptive optics and its astronomical applications. Topics include effects of atmospheric turbulence on astronomical images, basic principles of feedback control, wavefront sensors and correctors, laser guide stars, how to analyze and optimize performance of adaptive optics systems, and techniques for utilizing current and future systems for astronomical observations. (Formerly course 289C).")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("C. Max")
setCourse("292")
setTitle("Seminar (no credit)")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Seminar attended by faculty, graduate students, and upper-division undergraduate students.")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("297")
setTitle("Independent Study")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Independent study or research for graduate students who have not yet begun work on their theses. Students submit petition to sponsoring agency.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("299")
setTitle("Thesis Research")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Students submit petition to sponsoring agency.")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setDept("bioc")
setDiv("Upper-Division")
setCourse("100A")
setDescrip("Biochemistry and Molecular Biology")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Fundamentals of molecular biology, structure and function of nucleic acids, and protein structure. Designed for students preparing for research careers in biochemistry and molecular biology. Lecture: 3-1/2 hours; discussion: 1-1/4 hours.")
setPrereqs("Chemistry 8B or 108B; and Biology 20")
setInstruct("A. W. Scott")
setCourse("100B")
setTitle("Biochemistry and Molecular Biology")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Covers principles of protein function from ligand binding and enzyme mechanism, kinetics and regulation to membrane composition and membrane protein function. Lecture: 3-1/2 hours; discussion: 1-1/4 hours. (Formerly Biochemistry ).")
setPrereqs("course 100A")
setInstruct("C. Partch")
setCourse("100C")
setTitle("Biochemistry and Molecular Biology")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Biochemistry: intermediary metabolism and bioenergetics. How enzymatically catalyzed reactions are organized and regulated; how energy from molecules is extracted for chemical work. Lecture: 3-1/2 hours; discussion: 1-1/4 hours. (Formerly Biochemistry ).")
setPrereqs("course 100B")
setInstruct("C. Saltikov")
setCourse("110L")
setTitle("Advanced Biochemistry Laboratory")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("An introduction to the major techniques used in the isolation and characterization of biological components. Laboratory: 8 hours; lecture: 1-3/4 hours. Students are billed a materials fee.")
setPrereqs("course 100B and satisfaction of the Entry Level Writing and Composition requirements. Enrollment is restricted to chemistry majors in the biochemistry concentration. Other majors by permission")
setInstruct("O. Einarsdottir")
setDept("math")
setDiv("Lower-Division")
setCourse("2")
setDescrip("College Algebra for Calculus")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Operations on real numbers, complex numbers, polynomials, and rational expressions; exponents and radicals; solving linear and quadratic equations and inequalities; functions, algebra of functions, graphs; conic sections; mathematical models; sequences and series.")
setPrereqs("mathematics placement (MP) score of 100 or higher")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("2S")
setTitle("College Algebra for Calculus (2 credits)")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("This two-credit, stretch course offers students two quarters to master material covered in course 2: operations on real numbers, complex numbers, polynomials, and rational expressions; exponents and radicals; solving linear and quadratic equations and inequalities; functions, algebra of functions, graphs; conic sections; mathematical models; sequences and series. After successful completion of this course in the first quarter, students enroll in course 2 the following quarter to complete the sequence and earn an additional 5 credits.")
setPrereqs("mathematics placement (MP) score of 100 or higher")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("2T")
setTitle("Preparatory Math: Tutorial (2 credits)")
setTerms("F,W")
setDescrip("Independent study of algebra and modern mathematics using adaptive learning software. Instruction emphasizes clear mathematical communication and reasoning when working with sets, equations, functions, and graphs. Drop in labs, online forums, and readings provide opportunities for further learning and exploration.")
setPrereqs("mathematics placement (MP) score of 100 or higher")
setInstruct("D. Lewis")
setCourse("3")
setTitle("Precalculus")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Inverse functions and graphs; exponential and logarithmic functions, their graphs, and use in mathematical models of the real world; rates of change; trigonometry, trigonometric functions, and their graphs; and geometric series. Students cannot receive credit for both course 3 and Applied Mathematics and Statistics 3. Applied Mathematics and Statistics 3 can substitute for course 3.")
setPrereqs("course 2 or mathematics placement (MP) score of 200 or higher")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("4")
setTitle("Mathematics of Choice and Argument")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Techniques of analyzing and creating quantitative arguments. Application of probability theory to questions in justice, medicine, and economics. Analysis and avoidance of statistical bias. Understanding the application and limitations of quantitative techniques.")
setPrereqs("course 2, or mathematics placement (MP) score of 200 or higher, or AP Calculus AB examination score of 3 or higher")
setGe("SR")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("11A")
setTitle("Calculus with Applications")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("A modern course stressing conceptual understanding, relevance, and problem solving. The derivative of polynomial, exponential, and trigonometric functions of a single variable is developed and applied to a wide range of problems involving graphing, approximation, and optimization. Students cannot receive credit for both this course and course 19A or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 11A and 15A, or Economics 11A.")
setPrereqs("course 3 or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 3; or mathematics placement (MP) score of 300 or higher; or AP Calculus AB exam score of 3 or higher")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("11B")
setTitle("Calculus with Applications")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Starting with the fundamental theorem of calculus and related techniques, the integral of functions of a single variable is developed and applied to problems in geometry, probability, physics, and differential equations. Polynomial approximations, Taylor series, and their applications conclude the course. Students cannot receive credit for this course and course 19B, or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 11B and 15B, or Economics 11B.")
setPrereqs("course 11A or 19A or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 15A or AP Calculus AB exam score of 4 or 5, or BC exam score of 3 or higher, or IB Mathematics Higher Level exam score of 5 or higher")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("19A")
setTitle("Calculus for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("The limit of a function, calculating limits, continuity, tangents, velocities, and other instantaneous rates of change. Derivatives, the chain rule, implicit differentiation, higher derivatives. Exponential functions, inverse functions, and their derivatives. The mean value theorem, monotonic functions, concavity, and points of inflection. Applied maximum and minimum problems. Students cannot receive credit for both this course and course 11A or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 11A and 15A,or Economics 11A.")
setPrereqs("course 3; or mathematics placement (MP) score of 400 or higher; or AP Calculus AB exam score of 3 or higher")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("19B")
setTitle("Calculus for Science, Engineering, and Mathematics")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("The definite integral and the fundamental theorem of calculus. Areas, volumes. Integration by parts, trigonometric substitution, and partial fractions methods. Improper integrals. Sequences, series, absolute convergence and convergence tests. Power series, Taylor and Maclaurin series. Students cannot receive credit for both this course and course 11B, Applied Math and Statistics 11B and 15B, or Economics 11B.")
setPrereqs("course 19A or 20A or AP Calculus AB exam score of 4 or 5, or BC exam score of 3 or higher, or IB Mathematics Higher Level exam score of 5 of higher")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("20A")
setTitle("Honors Calculus")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Methods of proof, number systems, binomial and geometric sums. Sequences, limits, continuity, and the definite integral. The derivatives of the elementary functions, the fundamental theorem of calculus, and the main theorems of differential calculus.")
setPrereqs("mathematics placement (MP) score of 500 higher; or AP Calculus AB examination score of 4 or 5; or BC examination of 3 or higher; or IB Mathematics Higher Level examination score of 5 or higher")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("20B")
setTitle("Honors Calculus")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Orbital mechanics, techniques of integration, and separable differential equations. Taylor expansions and error estimates, the Gaussian integral, Gamma function and Stirling's formula. Series and power series, numerous applications to physics.")
setPrereqs("course 20A")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("21")
setTitle("Linear Algebra")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Systems of linear equations matrices, determinants. Introduces abstract vector spaces, linear transformation, inner products, the geometry of Euclidean space, and eigenvalues. Students cannot receive credit for this course and Applied Mathematics and Statistics 10 or 10A.")
setPrereqs("Mathematics 11A or 19A or 20A or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 11A or 15A")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("22")
setTitle("Introduction to Calculus of Several Variables")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Functions of several variables. Continuity and partial derivatives. The chain rule, gradient and directional derivative. Maxima and minima, including Lagrange multipliers. The double and triple integral and change of variables. Surface area and volumes. Applications from biology, chemistry, earth sciences, engineering, and physics. Students cannot receive credit for this course and course 23A.")
setPrereqs("course 11B or 19B or 20B or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 15B or AP calculus BC exam score of 4 or 5")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("23A")
setTitle("Vector Calculus")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Vectors in n-dimensional Euclidean space. The inner and cross products. The derivative of functions from n-dimensional to m-dimensional Euclidean space is studied as a linear transformation having matrix representation. Paths in 3-dimensions, arc length, vector differential calculus, Taylor's theorem in several variables, extrema of real-valued functions, constrained extrema and Lagrange multipliers, the implicit function theorem, some applications. Students cannot receive credit for this course and course 22. (Formerly Multivariable Calculus).")
setPrereqs("course 19B or 20B or AP calculus BC exam score of 4 or 5")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("23B")
setTitle("Vector Calculus")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Double integral, changing the order of integration. Triple integrals, maps of the plane, change of variables theorem, improper double integrals. Path integrals, line integrals, parametrized surfaces, area of a surface, surface integrals. Green's theorem, Stokes' theorem, conservative fields, Gauss' theorem. Applications to physics and differential equations, differential forms. (Formerly Multivariable Calculus).")
setPrereqs("course 23A")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("24")
setTitle("Ordinary Differential Equations")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("First and second order ordinary differential equations, with emphasis on the linear case. Methods of integrating factors, undetermined coefficients, variation of parameters, power series, numerical computation. Students cannot receive credit for this course and Applied Mathematics and Statistics 20.")
setPrereqs("course 22 or 23A; course 21 is recommended as preparation")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("99")
setTitle("Tutorial")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("99F")
setTitle("Tutorial (2 credits)")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setDiv("Upper-Division")
setCourse("100")
setDescrip("Introduction to Proof and Problem Solving")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Students learn the basic concepts and ideas necessary for upper-division mathematics and techniques of mathematical proof. Introduction to sets, relations, elementary mathematical logic, proof by contradiction, mathematical induction, and counting arguments.")
setPrereqs("satisfaction of the Entry Level Writing and Composition requirements; course 11A or 19A or 20A; and course 21 or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 10 or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 10A")
setGe("MF")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("101")
setTitle("Mathematical Problem Solving")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Students learn the strategies, tactics, skills and tools that mathematicians use when faced with a novel (new) problem. These include generalization, specialization, the optimization, invariance, symmetry, Dirichlet's box principle among others in the context of solving problems from number theory, geometry, calculus, combinatorics, probability, algebra, analysis, and graph theory. (Formerly, course 30).")
setPrereqs("courses 21 and 100")
setGe("PR-E")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("103A")
setTitle("Complex Analysis")
setTerms("W,S")
setDescrip("Complex numbers, analytic and harmonic functions, complex integration, the Cauchy integral formula, Laurent series, singularities and residues, conformal mappings. (Formerly course 103).")
setPrereqs("course 23B; and either course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("103B")
setTitle("Complex Analysis II (2 credits)")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Conformal mappings, the Riemann mapping theorem, Mobius transformations, Fourier series, Fourier and Laplace transforms, applications, and other topics as time permits.")
setPrereqs("course 103")
setInstruct("A. The Staff")
setCourse("105A")
setTitle("Real Analysis")
setTerms("F,W")
setDescrip("The basic concepts of one-variable calculus are treated rigorously. Set theory, the real number system, numerical sequences and series, continuity, differentiation.")
setPrereqs("course 22 or 23B and either course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("105B")
setTitle("Real Analysis")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Metric spaces, differentiation and integration of functions. The Riemann-Stieltjes integral. Sequences and series of functions.")
setPrereqs("course 105")
setInstruct("A. The Staff")
setCourse("105C")
setTitle("Real Analysis")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("The Stone-Weierstrass theorem, Fourier series, differentiation and integration of functions of several variables.")
setPrereqs("course 105")
setInstruct("B. The Staff")
setCourse("106")
setTitle("Systems of Ordinary Differential Equations")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Linear systems, exponentials of operators, existence and uniqueness, stability of equilibria, periodic attractors, and applications. (Formerly course 106A).")
setPrereqs("courses 21 and 24 (preferred) or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 10 and 20; and either course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("107")
setTitle("Partial Differential Equations")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Topics covered include first and second order linear partial differential equations, the heat equation, the wave equation, Laplace's equation, separation of variables, eigenvalue problems, Green's functions, Fourier series, special functions including Bessel and Legendre functions, distributions and transforms.")
setPrereqs("courses 21 and 24 (preferred) or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 10 and 20; and either course 100 or Computer Science 101; course 106 is recommended as preparation")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("110")
setTitle("Introduction to Number Theory")
setTerms("W,S")
setDescrip("Prime numbers, unique factorization, congruences with applications (e.g., to magic squares). Rational and irrational numbers. Continued fractions. Introduction to Diophantine equations. An introduction to some of the ideas and outstanding problems of modern mathematics.")
setPrereqs("course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("111A")
setTitle("Algebra")
setTerms("F,W")
setDescrip("Group theory including the Sylow theorem, the structure of abelian groups, and permutation groups.")
setPrereqs("course 21 or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 10 and either course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("111B")
setTitle("Algebra")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Introduction to rings and fields including polynomial rings, factorization, the classical geometric constructions, and Galois theory.")
setPrereqs("course 111")
setInstruct("A. The Staff")
setCourse("114")
setTitle("Introduction to Financial Mathematics")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Financial derivatives: contracts and options. Hedging and risk managment. Arbitrage, interest rate, and discounted value. Geometric random walk and Brownian motion as models of risky assets. Ito's formula. Initial boundary value problems for the heat and related partial differential equations. Self-financing replicating portfolio; Black-Scholes pricing of European options. Dividends. Implied volatility. American options as free boundary problems. Corequisite(s): Applied Mathematics and Statistics 131 or Computer Engineering 107.")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("115")
setTitle("Graph Theory")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Graph theory, trees, vertex and edge colorings, Hamilton cycles, Eulerian circuits, decompositions into isomorphic subgraphs, extremal problems, cages, Ramsey theory, Cayley's spanning tree formula, planar graphs, Euler's formula, crossing numbers, thickness, splitting numbers, magic graphs, graceful trees, rotations, and genus of graphs.")
setPrereqs("course 21 or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 10 and either course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("116")
setTitle("Combinatorics")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Based on induction and elementary counting techniques: counting subsets, partitions, and permutations; recurrence relations and generating functions; the principle of inclusion and exclusion; Polya enumeration; Ramsey theory or enumerative geometry.")
setPrereqs("course 100. Enrollment restricted to sophomores juniors, and seniors. Familiarity with basic group theory recommended")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("117")
setTitle("Advanced Linear Algebra")
setTerms("F,S")
setDescrip("Review of abstract vector spaces. Dual spaces, bilinear forms, and the associated geometry. Normal forms of linear mappings. Introduction to tensor products and exterior algebras.")
setPrereqs("course 21 or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 10 and either course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("118")
setTitle("Advanced Number Theory")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Topics include divisibility and congruences, arithmetical functions, quadratic residues and quadratic reciprocity, quadratic forms and representations of numbers as sums of squares, Diophantine approximation and transcendence theory, quadratic fields. Additional topics as time permits.")
setPrereqs("course 110 or 111")
setInstruct("A. The Staff")
setCourse("120")
setTitle("Coding Theory")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("An introduction to mathematical theory of coding. Construction and properties of various codes, such as cyclic, quadratic residue, linear, Hamming, and Golay codes; weight enumerators; connections with modern algebra and combinatorics.")
setPrereqs("course 21")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("121A")
setTitle("Differential Geometry")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Topics include Euclidean space, tangent vectors, directional derivatives, curves and differential forms in space, mappings. Curves, the Frenet formulas, covariant derivatives, frame fields, the structural equations. The classification of space curves up to rigid motions. Vector fields and differentiable forms on surfaces; the shape operator. Gaussian and mean curvature. The theorem Egregium; global classification of surfaces in three space by curvature.")
setPrereqs("courses 21 and 23B and either course 100 or Computer Science 101. Course 105A strongly recommended")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("121B")
setTitle("Differential Geometry and Topology")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Examples of surfaces of constant curvature, surfaces of revolutions, minimal surfaces. Abstract manifolds; integration theory; Riemannian manifolds. Total curvature and geodesics; the Euler characteristic, the Gauss-Bonnet theorem. Length-minimizing properties of geodesics, complete surfaces, curvature and conjugate points covering surfaces. Surfaces of constant curvature; the theorems of Bonnet and Hadamard.")
setPrereqs("course 121")
setInstruct("A. The Staff")
setCourse("124")
setTitle("Introduction to Topology")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Topics include introduction to point set topology (topological spaces, continuous maps, connectedness, compactness), homotopy relation, definition and calculation of fundamental groups and homology groups, Euler characteristic, classification of orientable and nonorientable surfaces, degree of maps, and Lefschetz fixed-point theorem.")
setPrereqs("course 100; course 111A recommended")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("128A")
setTitle("Classical Geometry: Euclidean and Non-Euclidean")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Euclidean, projective, spherical, and hyperbolic (non-Euclidean) geometries. Begins with the thirteen books of Euclid. Surveys the other geometries. Attention paid to constructions and visual intuition as well as logical foundations. Rigid motions and projective transformations covered.")
setPrereqs("either course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("128B")
setTitle("Classical Geometry: Projective")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Theorems of Desargue, Pascal, and Pappus; projectivities; homogeneous and affine coordinates; conics; relation to perspective drawing and some history.")
setPrereqs("course 21")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("129")
setTitle("Algebraic Geometry")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Algebraic geometry of affine and projective curves, including conics and elliptic curves; Bezout's theorem; coordinate rings and Hillbert's Nullstellensatz; affine and projective varieties; and regular and singular varieties. Other topics, such as blow-ups and algebraic surfaces as time permits.")
setPrereqs("courses 21 and 100")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("130")
setTitle("Celestial Mechanics")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Solves the two-body (or Kepler) problem, then moves onto the N-body problem where there are many open problems. Includes central force laws; orbital elements; conservation of linear momentum, energy, and angular momentum; the Lagrange-Jacobi formula; Sundman's theorem for total collision; virial theorem; the three-body problem; Jacobi coordinates; solutions of Euler and of Lagrange; and restricted three-body problem.")
setPrereqs("courses 19A-B and course 23A or Physics 5A or 6A; courses 21 and 24 strongly recommended")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("134")
setTitle("Cryptography")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Introduces different methods in cryptography (shift cipher, affine cipher, Vigenere cipher, Hill cipher, RSA cipher, ElGamal cipher, knapsack cipher). The necessary material from number theory and probability theory is developed in the course. Common methods to attack ciphers discussed.")
setPrereqs("course 100 or Computer Science 101; course 110 is recommended as preparation")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("140")
setTitle("Industrial Mathematics")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Introduction to mathematical modeling of industrial problems. Problems in air quality remediation, image capture and reproduction, and crystallization are modeled as ordinary and partial differential equations then analyzed using a combination of qualitative and quantitative methods.")
setPrereqs("course 24 and either course 100 or Computer Science 101, and course 105")
setInstruct("A. The Staff")
setCourse("145")
setTitle("Introductory Chaos Theory")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("The Lorenz and Rossler attractors, measures of chaos, attractor reconstruction, and applications from the sciences. Students cannot receive credit for this course and Applied Mathematics and Statistics 114.")
setPrereqs("course 22 or 23A; course 21; course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setConcReq("course 145L")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("145L")
setTitle("Introductory Chaos Laboratory (1 credit)")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Laboratory sequence illustrating topics covered in course 145. One three-hour session per week in microcomputer laboratory. ")
setConcReq("course 145")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("148")
setTitle("Numerical Analysis")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("A survey of the basic numerical methods which are used to solve scientific problems, including mathematical analysis and computing assignments. Some prior experience with Matlab (or similar) is helpful but not required. Some typical topics are: computer arithmetic; Newton's method for non-linear equations; linear algebra; interpolation and approximation; numerical differentiation and integration; numerical solutions of systems of ordinary differential equations and some partial differential equations; convergence and error bounds.")
setPrereqs("course 22 or 23A; course 21 and 24 or Applied Mathematics and Statistics 10 and 20; course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setConcReq("course 148L")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("148L")
setTitle("Numerical Analysis Laboratory (1 credit)")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Laboratory sequence illustrating topics covered in course 148. One three-hour session per week in the computer laboratory. ")
setConcReq("course 148")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("160")
setTitle("Mathematical Logic I")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Propositional and predicate calculus. Resolution, completeness, compactness, and Lowenheim-Skolem theorem. Recursive functions, Godel incompleteness theorem. Undecidable theories. Hilbert's 10th problem.")
setPrereqs("course 100 or Computer Science 101")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("161")
setTitle("Mathematical Logic II")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Naive set theory and its limitations (Russell's paradox); construction of numbers as sets; cardinal and ordinal numbers; cardinal and ordinal arithmetic; transfinite induction; axiom systems for set theory, with particular emphasis on the axiom of choice and the regularity axiom and their consequences (such as, the Banach-Tarski paradox); continuum hypothesis.")
setPrereqs("course 100 or equivalent, or by permission of instructor")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("181")
setTitle("History of Mathematics")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("A survey from a historical point of view of various developments in mathematics. Specific topics and periods to vary yearly.")
setPrereqs("course 19B or 20B")
setGe("TA")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("188")
setTitle("Supervised Teaching")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Supervised tutoring in self-paced courses. May not be repeated for credit. Students submit petition to sponsoring agency.")
setGe("PR-S")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("189")
setTitle("ACE Program Service Learning (2 credits)")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Students participate in training and development to co-facilitate collaborative learning in ACE chemistry discussion sections and midterm/exam review sessions. Students are role models for students pursuing science- and math-intensive majors.")
setPrereqs("Prior participation in ACE; good academic standing; no non-passing grades in prior quarter")
setEnrollRestrict("sophomores, juniors, and seniors")
setGe("PR-S")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("193A")
setTitle("Senior Seminar Education Track (3 credits)")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Designed for education-track mathematics majors. Students develop worksheets, present mathematical concepts, and write a final paper consisting of their reflections and learning outcome of both theory and practice in teaching of precalculus.")
setPrereqs("course 103A or 105A or 111A, and satisfaction of the Entry Level Writing and Composition requirements")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("193B")
setTitle("Senior Seminar Education Track (3 credits)")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("For education-track, mathematics majors. Students develop worksheets, present mathematical concepts, and write a final paper consisting of their reflections and learning outcome of both theory and practice in the teaching of precalculus.")
setPrereqs("course 103 or 103A or 105A or 111A; and 193A; and satisfaction of the Entry Level Writing and Composition requirements")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("194")
setTitle("Senior Seminar")
setTerms("W,S")
setDescrip("Designed to expose the student to topics not normally covered in the standard courses. The format varies from year to year. In recent years each student has written a paper and presented a lecture on it to the class.")
setPrereqs("satisfaction of the Entry Level Writing and Composition requirements; course 103 or 103A or 105A or 111A")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("195")
setTitle("Senior Thesis")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Students research a mathematical topic under the guidance of a faculty sponsor and write a senior thesis demonstrating knowledge of the material.")
setPrereqs("satisfaction of the Entry Level Writing and Composition requirements. Students submit petition to sponsoring agency")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("199")
setTitle("Tutorial")
setTerms("F,W,S")
setDescrip("Students submit petition to sponsoring agency.")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setDiv("Graduate")
setCourse("200")
setDescrip("Algebra I")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Group theory: subgroups, cosets, normal subgroups, homomorphisms, isomorphisms, quotient groups, free groups, generators and relations, group actions on a set. Sylow theorems, semidirect products, simple groups, nilpotent groups, and solvable groups. Ring theory: Chinese remainder theorem, prime ideals, localization. Euclidean domains, PIDs, UFDs, polynomial rings.")
setPrereqs("courses 111A and 117 are recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("201")
setTitle("Algebra II")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Vector spaces, linear transformations, eigenvalues and eigenvectors, the Jordan canonical form, bilinear forms, quadratic forms, real symmetric forms and real symmetric matrices, orthogonal transformations and orthogonal matrices, Euclidean space, Hermitian forms and Hermitian matrices, Hermitian spaces, unitary transformations and unitary matrices, skewsymmetric forms, tensor products of vector spaces, tensor algebras, symmetric algebras, exterior algebras, Clifford algebras and spin groups.")
setPrereqs("Course 200 is recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("202")
setTitle("Algebra III")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Module theory: Submodules, quotient modules, module homomorphisms, generators of modules, direct sums, free modules, torsion modules, modules over PIDs, and applications to rational and Jordan canonical forms. Field theory: field extensions, algebraic and transcendental extensions, splitting fields, algebraic closures, separable and normal extensions, the Galois theory, finite fields, Galois theory of polynomials.")
setPrereqs("Course 201 is recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("203")
setTitle("Algebra IV")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Topics include tensor product of modules over rings, projective modules and injective modules, Jacobson radical, Wedderburns' theorem, category theory, Noetherian rings, Artinian rings, affine varieties, projective varieties, Hilbert's Nullstellensatz, prime spectrum, Zariski topology, discrete valuation rings, and Dedekind domains.")
setPrereqs("courses 200, 201, and 202")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("204")
setTitle("Analysis I")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Completeness and compactness for real line; sequences and infinite series of functions; Fourier series; calculus on Euclidean space and the implicit function theorem; metric spaces and the contracting mapping theorem; the Arzela-Ascoli theorem; basics of general topological spaces; the Baire category theorem; Urysohn's lemma; and Tychonoff's theorem.")
setPrereqs("courses105A and 105B are recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("205")
setTitle("Analysis II")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Lebesgue measure theory, abstract measure theory, measurable functions, integration, space of absolutely integrable functions, dominated convergence theorem, convergence in measure, Riesz representation theorem, product measure and Fubini 's theorem. Lp spaces, derivative of a measure, the Radon-Nikodym theorem, and the fundamental theorem of calculus.")
setPrereqs("course 204")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("206")
setTitle("Analysis III")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Banach spaces, Hahn-Banach theorem, uniform boundedness theorem, the open mapping and closed graph theorems, weak and weak* topology, the Banach-Alaoglu theorem, Hilbert spaces, self-adjoint operators, compact operators, spectral theory, Fredholm operators, spaces of distributions and the Fourier transform, and Sobolev spaces.")
setPrereqs("Courses 204 and 205 recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("207")
setTitle("Complex Analysis")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Holomorphic and harmonic functions, Cauchy's integral theorem, the maximum principle and its consequences, conformal mapping, analytic continuation, the Riemann mapping theorem.")
setPrereqs("Course 103 is recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("208")
setTitle("Manifolds I")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Definition of manifolds; the tangent bundle; the inverse function theorem and the implicit function theorem; transversality; Sard's theorem and the Whitney embedding theorem; vector fields, flows, and the Lie bracket; Frobenius's theorem. Course 204 recommended for preparation.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("209")
setTitle("Manifolds II")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Tensor algebra. Differential forms and associated formalism of pullback, wedge product, exterior derivative, Stokes theorem, integration. Cartan's formula for Lie derivative. Cohomology via differential forms. The Poincaré lemma and the Mayer-Vietoris sequence. Theorems of deRham and Hodge.")
setPrereqs("course 208")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("210")
setTitle("Manifolds III")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("The fundamental group, covering space theory and van Kampen's theorem (with a discussion of free and amalgamated products of groups), CW complexes, higher homotopy groups, cellular and singular cohomology, the Eilenberg-Steenrod axioms, computational tools including Mayer-Vietoris, cup products, Poincaré duality, the Lefschetz fixed point theorem, the exact homotopy sequence of a fibration and the Hurewicz isomorphism theorem, and remarks on characteristic classes.")
setPrereqs("Courses 208 and 209 recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("211")
setTitle("Algebraic Topology")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Continuation of course 210. Topics include theory of characteristic classes of vector bundles, cobordism theory, and homotopy theory.")
setPrereqs("Courses 200, 201, and 202 recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("212")
setTitle("Differential Geometry")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Principal bundles, associated bundles and vector bundles, connections and curvature on principal and vector bundles. More advanced topics include: introduction to cohomology, the Chern-Weil construction and characteristic classes, the Gauss-Bonnet theorem or Hodge theory, eigenvalue estimates for Beltrami Laplacian, and comparison theorems in Riemannian geometry.")
setPrereqs("course 208")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("213A")
setTitle("Partial Differential Equations I")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("First of the two PDE courses covering basically Part I in Evans' book; Partial Differential Equations; which includes transport equations; Laplace equations; heat equations; wave equations; characteristics of nonlinear first-order PDE; Hamilton-Jacobi equations; conservation laws; some methods for solving equations in closed form; and the Cauchy-Kovalevskaya theorem. Courses 106 and 107 are recommended as preparation.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("213B")
setTitle("Partial Differential Equations II")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Second course of the PDE series covering basically most of Part II in Evans' book and some topics in nonlinear PDE including Sobolev spaces, Sobolev inequalities, existence, regularity and a priori estimates of solutions to second order elliptic PDE, parabolic equations, hyperbolic equations and systems of conservation laws, and calculus of variations and its applications to PDE.")
setPrereqs("Courses 106, 107, and 213A are recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("214")
setTitle("Theory of Finite Groups")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Nilpotent groups, solvable groups, Hall subgroups, the Frattini subgroup, the Fitting subgroup, the Schur-Zassenhaus theorem, fusion in p-subgroups, the transfer map, Frobenius theorem on normal p-complements.")
setPrereqs("Courses 200 and 201 recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("215")
setTitle("Operator Theory")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Operators on Banach spaces and Hilbert spaces. The spectral theorem. Compact and Fredholm operators. Other special classes of operators.")
setPrereqs("Courses 204, 205, 206, and 207 are recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("216")
setTitle("Advanced Analysis")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Topics include: the Lebesgue set, the Marcinkiewicz interpolation theorem, singular integrals, the Calderon-Zygmund theorem, Hardy Littlewood-Sobolev theorem, pseudodifferential operators, compensated compactness, concentration compactness, and applications to PDE.")
setPrereqs("Courses 204, 205, and 206 recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("217")
setTitle("Advanced Elliptic Partial Differential Equations")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Topics include elliptic equations, existence of weak solutions, the Lax-Milgram theorem, interior and boundary regularity, maximum principles, the Harnack inequality, eigenvalues for symmetric and non-symmetric elliptic operators, calculus of variations (first variation: Euler-Lagrange equations, second variation: existence of minimizers). Other topics covered as time permits.")
setPrereqs("Courses 204, 205, and 206 recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("218")
setTitle("Advanced Parabolic and Hyperbolic Partial Differential Equations")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Topics include: linear evolution equations, second order parabolic equations, maximum principles, second order hyperbolic equations, propagation of singularities, hyperbolic systems of first order, semigroup theory, systems of conservation laws, Riemann problem, simple waves, rarefaction waves, shock waves, Riemann invariants, and entropy criteria. Other topics covered as time permits.")
setPrereqs("courses 205 and 206")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("219")
setTitle("Nonlinear Functional Analysis")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Topological methods in nonlinear partial differential equations, including degree theory, bifurcation theory, and monotonicity. Topics also include variational methods in the solution of nonlinear partial differential equations.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("220A")
setTitle("Representation Theory I")
setTerms("S")
setDescrip("Lie groups and Lie algebras, and their finite dimensional representations.")
setPrereqs("courses 200, 201, and 202. Courses 225A and 227 recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("220B")
setTitle("Representation Theory II")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Lie groups and Lie algebras, and their finite dimensional representations.")
setPrereqs("course 220A")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("222A")
setTitle("Algebraic Number Theory")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Topics include algebraic integers, completions, different and discriminant, cyclotomic fields, parallelotopes, the ideal function, ideles and adeles, elementary properties of zeta functions and L-series, local class field theory, global class field theory. Courses 200, 201, and 202 are recommended as preparation.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("222B")
setTitle("Algebraic Number Theory")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Topics include geometric methods in number theory, finiteness theorems, analogues of Riemann-Roch for algebraic fields (after A. Weil), inverse Galois problem (Belyi theorem) and consequences.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("223A")
setTitle("Algebraic Geometry I")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Topics include examples of algebraic varieties, elements of commutative algebra, local properties of algebraic varieties, line bundles and sheaf cohomology, theory of algebraic curves. Weekly problem solving. Courses 200, 201, 202, and 208 are recommended as preparation.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("223B")
setTitle("Algebraic Geometry II")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("A continuation of course 223A. Topics include theory of schemes and sheaf cohomology, formulation of the Riemann-Roch theorem, birational maps, theory of surfaces. Weekly problem solving.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("225A")
setTitle("Lie Algebras")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Basic concepts of Lie algebras. Engel's theorem, Lie's theorem, Weyl's theorem are proved. Root space decomposition for semi-simple algebras, root systems and the classification theorem for semi-simple algebras over the complex numbers. Isomorphism and conjugacy theorems.")
setPrereqs("Courses 201 and 202 recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("225B")
setTitle("Infinite Dimensional Lie Algebras")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Finite dimensional semi-simple Lie algebras: PBW theorem, generators and relations, highest weight representations, Weyl character formula. Infinite dimensional Lie algebras: Heisenberg algebras, Virasoro algebras, loop algebras, affine Kac-Moody algebras, vertex operator representations.")
setPrereqs("course 225A")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("226A")
setTitle("Infinite Dimensional Lie Algebras and Quantum Field Theory I")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Introduction to the infinite-dimensional Lie algebras that arise in modern mathematics and mathematical physics: Heisenberg and Virasoro algebras, representations of the Heisenberg algebra, Verma modules over the Virasoro algebra, the Kac determinant formula, and unitary and discrete series representations.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("226B")
setTitle("Infinite Dimensional Lie Algebras and Quantum Field Theory II")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Continuation of course 226A: Kac-Moody and affine Lie algebras and their representations, integrable modules, representations via vertex operators, modular invariance of characters, and introduction to vertex operator algebras.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("227")
setTitle("Lie Groups")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Lie groups and algebras, the exponential map, the adjoint action, Lie's three theorems, Lie subgroups, the maximal torus theorem, the Weyl group, some topology of Lie groups, some representation theory: Schur's Lemma, the Peter-Weyl theorem, roots, weights, classification of Lie groups, the classical groups.")
setPrereqs("courses 200, 201, 204, and 208")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("228")
setTitle("Lie Incidence Geometries")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Linear incidence geometry is introduced. Linear and classical groups are reviewed, and geometries associated with projective and polar spaces are introduced. Characterizations are obtained.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("229")
setTitle("Kac-Moody Algebras")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Theory of Kac-Moody algebras and their representations. The Weil-Kac character formula. Emphasis on representations of affine superalgebras by vertex operators. Connections to combinatorics, PDE, the monster group. The Virasoro algebra.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("232")
setTitle("Morse Theory")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Classical Morse Theory. The fundamental theorems relating critical points to the topology of a manifold are treated in detail. The Bott Periodicity Theorem. A specialized course offered once every few years.")
setPrereqs("Courses 208, 209, 210, 211, and 212 recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("233")
setTitle("Random Matrix Theory")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Classical matrix ensembles; Wigner semi-circle law; method of moments. Gaussian ensembles. Method of orthogonal polynomials; Gaudin lemma. Distribution functions for spacings and largest eigenvalue. Asymptotics and Riemann-Hilbert problem. Painleve theory and the Tracy-Widom distribution. Selberg's Integral. Matrix ensembles related to classical groups; symmetric functions theory. Averages of characteristic polynomials. Fundamentals of free probability theory. Overview of connections with physics, combinatorics, and number theory.")
setPrereqs("courses 103, 204, and 205; course 117 recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("234")
setTitle("Riemann Surfaces")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("Riemann surfaces, conformal maps, harmonic forms, holomorphic forms, the Reimann-Roch theorem, the theory of moduli.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("235")
setTitle("Dynamical Systems Theory")
setTerms("W")
setDescrip("An introduction to the qualitative theory of systems of ordinary differential equations. Structural stability, critical elements, stable manifolds, generic properties, bifurcations of generic arcs.")
setPrereqs("courses 203 and 208")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("238")
setTitle("Elliptic Functions and Modular Forms")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("The course, aimed at second-year graduate students, will cover the basic facts about elliptic functions and modular forms. The goal is to provide the student with foundations suitable for further work in advanced number theory, in conformal field theory, and in the theory of Riemann surfaces.")
setPrereqs("courses 200, 201, 202, and either 207 or 103A are recommended as preparation")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("239")
setTitle("Homological Algebra")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Homology and cohomology theories have proven to be powerful tools in many fields (topology, geometry, number theory, algebra). Independent of the field, these theories use the common language of homological algebra. The aim of this course is to acquaint the participants with basic concepts of category theory and homological algebra, as follows: chain complexes, homology, homotopy, several (co)homology theories (topological spaces, manifolds, groups, algebras, Lie groups), projective and injective resolutions, derived functors (Ext and Tor). Depending on time, spectral sequences or derived categories may also be treated. Courses 200 and 202 strongly recommended.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("240A")
setTitle("Representations of Finite Groups I")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Introduces ordinary representation theory of finite groups (over the complex numbers). Main topics are characters, orthogonality relations, character tables, induction and restriction, Frobenius reciprocity, Mackey's formula, Clifford theory, Schur indicator, Schur index, Artin's and Braver's induction theorems. Recommended: successful completion of courses 200-202.")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("240B")
setTitle("Representations of Finite Groups II")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Introduces modular representation theory of finite groups (over a field of positive characteristic). Main topics are Grothendieck groups, Brauer characters, Brauer character table, projective covers, Brauer-Cartan triangle, relative projectivity, vertices, sources, Green correspondence, Green's indecomposability theorem. Recommended completion of courses 200-203 and 240A.")
setPrereqs("Courses 200, 201, 202, 203, and 240A recommended")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("246")
setTitle("Representations of Algebras")
setTerms("*")
setDescrip("Material includes associative algebras and their modules; projective and injective modules; projective covers; injective hulls; Krull-Schmidt Theorem; Cartan matrix; semisimple algebras and modules; radical, simple algebras; symmetric algebras; quivers and their representations; Morita Theory; and basic algebras.")
setPrereqs("courses 200, 201, and 202")
setEnrollRestrict("graduate students")
setInstruct("The Staff")
setCourse("248")
setTitle("Symplectic Geometry")
setTerms("F")
setDescrip("Basic definitions. Darboux theorem. Basic examples: cotangent bundles, Kähler manifolds and co-adjoint orbits. Normal form theorems. Hamiltonian group actions, moment maps. Reduction by symmetry groups. Atiyah-Guillemin-Sternberg convexity. Introduction to Floer homological methods. Relations with other geometries including contact, Poisson, and Kähler geometry.")
